The TestCase is actually exercising a program,
so the setup looks like this:

public class ReadAndCompareTests
  extends TestCase
{
  CommentMerge commentMerge;

  StringWriter testWriter;

  public ReadAndCompareTests(String name) {
    super(name);
  }

  public CommentMerge createInstance()
    throws Exception
 {
    return new CommentMerge();
  }

  protected void setUp() throws Exception {
    super.setUp();
    commentMerge = createInstance();
  }

  protected void tearDown() throws Exception {
    commentMerge = null;
    super.tearDown();
  }

When running this test, a number of errors are generated. The
app&#39;s error-report is then compared to a saved error report.
There is a match, and the test succeeds.
  public void test4_HierarchyCompare() throws Exception {
    commentMerge.execute(
      &quot;-specpath test/specSrc &quot; +
      &quot;-codePath test/codeSrc &quot; +
      &quot;test/specSrc/AnonClass.java &quot; +
      &quot;-subpackages smallpkg &quot; +
      &quot;-checkOnly &quot;
    );
    String result = testWriter.getBuffer() + &quot;&quot;;

    DocumentBuffer docBuffer =
       nio.readDocument(expected+&quot;4_compareWithError.txt&quot;);
    String expect = docBuffer.getCharBuffer()+&quot;&quot;;
    assertEquals(&quot;Hierarchy compare&quot;, expect, result);
  }

The next test then fails in unexpected fashion, because the
ErrorHandler object has an &quot;error found&quot; flag set.
  public void test2_CodeRead() throws Exception {
     commentMerge.execute(
      &quot;-specpath test/specSrc &quot; +
      &quot;-codePath test/codeSrc &quot; +
      &quot;test/specSrc/AnonClass.java &quot; +
      &quot;-subpackages smallpkg &quot; +
      &quot;-echoCode -lax&quot;
    );
    String result = testWriter.getBuffer() + &quot;&quot;;
    ....

(The app dies with &quot;invalid program option&quot;, because after
examining the options -- which in this case are correct --
the program checks to see whether and error has been found.
With a clean, new ErrorHandler, the error flag is clear. (The
test ran perfectly until the one ahead of it was added. The
debugger then showed that the error flag was set when
running the code.)

To solve the problem, I added this method, and invoked it at
the beginning of each test method:
  protected void init() {
    commentMerge.errorHandler = new CommentMergeErrorHandler();
    testWriter = new StringWriter();
    commentMerge.setWriter(testWriter);
  }

The tests are now working, but it looks to me like setup() isn&#39;t being
run for each test method.
